{"title_page": "National Museum of American Jewish History", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Jewish Museum (disambiguation){{!}}Jewish Museum}}\n{{coord|39.950288|-75.148593|display=title}}\n{{Infobox museum\n| name             = [[File:National Museum of American Jewish History logo.jpg|250px|National Museum of American Jewish History]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = \n| imagesize        = 200\n| caption          = \n| alt              = \n| map_type         = Philadelphia\n| map_caption      = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_size         =\n| coordinates      = {{coord|39.950288|-75.148593|display=inline}}\n| established      = {{Start date|1976}}\n| dissolved        = \n| location         = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| type             = [[Jewish]] Museum\n| collection       = 20,000\n| visitors         = 126,000 (2011)<ref>{{cite news|last=Salisbury|first=Stephan|title=Amid struggles, Jewish museum strives for broader appeal|url=http://articles.philly.com/2012-12-03/news/35550175_1_michael-rosenzweig-ivy-l-barsky-jewish-museum|accessdate=26 March 2013|newspaper=Philadelphia Inquirer|date=3 December 2012}}</ref> \n| director         = Dr. Misha Galperin (Interim CEO)\n| president        = \n| curator          = Josh Perelman\n| owner            =\n| publictransit    = {{rint|septa|60px}} [[5th Street (SEPTA Market\u2013Frankford Line station)|5th Street]]: {{Rail color box|system=SEPTA|line=Market-Frankford}} {{bus icon|12px}} {{rint|septa|60px}} [[SEPTA]] bus: {{SEPTA bus link|17|33|38|44|48}}<br>{{bus icon|12px}} [[Philly PHLASH]] \n| car_park         = \n| network          = \n| website          = [http://www.nmajh.org/ www.nmajh.org]\n}}\n\nThe '''National Museum of American Jewish History''' ('''NMAJH''') is a [[Smithsonian#Museums|Smithsonian-affiliated museum]] at 101 South Independence Mall East (S. 5th Street) at [[Market Street (Philadelphia)|Market Street]] in [[Center City, Philadelphia|Center City]] [[Philadelphia]].  It was founded in 1976. \n\nIn March 2020, The National Museum of American Jewish History filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, seeking relief from debt incurred by the construction of its Independence Mall home. The museum claims that it owes $30 million to bondholders and $500,000 to unsecured creditors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/news/philadelphia-jewish-museum-bankruptcy-debt-20200302.html|title=National Museum of American Jewish History files for bankruptcy protection|last=Salisbury|first=Stephan|website=https://www.inquirer.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==Building==\n[[File:National Museum of American Jewish History.jpg|thumb|left|275px|The new building in 2013]]\n\nWith its founding in 1976, the then\u2013{{convert|15000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} museum shared a building with the [[Congregation Mikveh Israel]].<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|date=2010-11-11 |title=Life, Liberty and the Pursuit of Identity |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/12/arts/design/12museum.html |first=Edward |last=Rothstein |work=The New York Times |accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, it was announced that the museum would be moved to a new building to be built at Fifth Street and [[Market Street (Philadelphia)|Market Street]] on the [[Independence Mall (Philadelphia)|Independence Mall]]. The site was originally owned by CBS' [[KYW-AM|KYW radio]] and [[KYW-TV]]. The project broke ground on September 30, 2007.<ref>{{cite web |date=2007-08-01 |title=The Time has Come for a Groundbreaking Event |url=http://www.nmajh.org/weblog/press/2007_08_01_archive.html |publisher=National Museum of American Jewish History |accessdate=2010-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119091557/http://www.nmajh.org/weblog/press/2007_08_01_archive.html |archivedate=2010-11-19 }}</ref> The {{convert|100000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} glass and [[terra-cotta]] building was designed by [[James Polshek]] and includes an atrium, a {{convert|25000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} area for exhibits, a Center for Jewish Education, and a theater.<ref>{{cite news|date=2010-11-14 |title=Building and message at odds |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/20101114_Building_and_message_at_odds.html |first=Inga |last=Saffron |work=The Philadelphia Inquirer |accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref> The structural engineer was Leslie E. Robertson Associates.\n\nThe project, including endowment, cost $150 million.<ref>{{cite news|date=2008-07-02 |title=Spielberg group gives $1M to Jewish history museum |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/stories/2008/06/30/daily34.html |work=Philadelphia Business Journal |accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref> The opening ceremony was held November 14, 2010 and was attended by over 1,000 people, including Vice President [[Joe Biden]], Mayor [[Michael Nutter]], Governor [[Ed Rendell]], and Rabbi [[Irving Greenberg]].<ref name=\"Opening\">{{cite news|date=2010-11-15 |title=Biden among notables attending opening ceremony of National Museum of American Jewish History |url=http://www.philly.com/inquirer/local/pa/20101115_Biden_among_notables_attending_opening_ceremony_of_National_Museum_of_American_Jewish_History.html |first=Howard |last=Shapiro |work=The Philadelphia Inquirer |accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref> The building opened to the public November 26, 2010.<ref name=\"Opening\" />\n\n==Exhibitions==\nExhibits use pieces from the museum's collection which includes over 20,000 objects and ranges from the Colonial period to the present day.<ref>{{cite web|date=2008-01-12 |title=Alongside the History of the Nation, the Story of Jewish Immigrants |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/12/us/12religion.html?_r=1&scp=7&sq=National%20Museum%20of%20American%20Jewish%20History%20&st=cse |first=Jon |last=Hurdle |work=The New York Times |accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref> Exhibits focus on Jews in America. Professor [[Jonathan Sarna]] of [[Brandeis University]] led the development of the core exhibit for the museum.\n\n'''To Bigotry No Sanction: George Washington and Religious Freedom'''\n\nFrom June 29 through September 30, 2012, the NMAJH held a special exhibition that featured one of the most important documents pertaining to religious freedom in the United States. The letter was written in 1790 to the Hebrew Congregation in [[Newport, Rhode Island]], addressing the new country's religious freedom.<ref>[http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/US-Israel/bigotry.html \"Bigotry\"] on the Jewish Virtual Library website</ref> The letter expressed the new government's commitment for religious freedom and equality for all faiths. The exhibition included numerous artifacts as well as early printings of the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]] and the [[Constitution of the United States|Constitution]].<ref>[http://www.nmajh.org/religiousfreedom/ \"To Bigotry No Sanction\"] on the Museum website</ref>\n\n==From the Core Exhibition in 2010==\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"175px\" heights=\"175px\">\nFile:Hanukkah lamp from Lodz, Poland, prior to 1881, silver, National Museum of American Jewish History.JPG|Hanukkah lamp from Lodz, Poland, prior to 1881, silver\nFile:Hanukkah menorah, Russia, 1890, brass, National Museum of American Jewish History.JPG|Hanukkah menorah, Russia, 1890, brass\nFile:Kiddush cup from Russia, engraved sterling silver, National Museum of American Jewish History.JPG|Kiddush cup from Russia, engraved sterling silver\nFile:Portrait of Joyce Mears Myers by Edward Green Malbone, c. 1803, oil on ivory.JPG|Portrait of Joyce Mears Myers by Edward Green Malbone, c. 1803, oil on ivory. No longer on view. \nFile:Silver menorah, William Gale and Sons, c. 1852, National Museum of American Jewish History.JPG|Silver menorah, William Gale and Sons, c. 1852\nFile:Torah finials, c. 1850, silver, National Museum of American Jewish History.jpg|Torah finials, c. 1850, silver\nFile:Tzedakah (charity) box, Charleston, 1820, silver, National Museum of American Jewish History.JPG|Tzedakah (charity) box or Kupat Tzedakah, Charleston, 1820, silver\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Museum of American Jewish Military History]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|National Museum of American Jewish History}}\n*{{official website}}\n\n{{Philadelphia}}\n{{Museums in Pennsylvania|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:National Museum Of American Jewish History}}\n[[Category:Ethnic museums in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:History museums in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Jewish-American history]]\n[[Category:Jewish history organizations]]\n[[Category:Jewish museums in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Museums established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Museums in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Old City, Philadelphia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Jewish Museum (disambiguation){{!}}Jewish Museum}}\n{{coord|39.950288|-75.148593|display=title}}\n{{Infobox museum\n| name             = [[File:National Museum of American Jewish History logo.jpg|250px|National Museum of American Jewish History]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = \n| imagesize        = 200\n| caption          = \n| alt              = \n| map_type         = Philadelphia\n| map_caption      = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_size         =\n| coordinates      = {{coord|39.950288|-75.148593|display=inline}}\n| established      = {{Start date|1976}}\n| dissolved        = \n| location         = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| type             = [[Jewish]] Museum\n| collection       = 20,000\n| visitors         = 126,000 (2011)<ref>{{cite news|last=Salisbury|first=Stephan|title=Amid struggles, Jewish museum strives for broader appeal|url=http://articles.philly.com/2012-12-03/news/35550175_1_michael-rosenzweig-ivy-l-barsky-jewish-museum|accessdate=26 March 2013|newspaper=Philadelphia Inquirer|date=3 December